com.ibm.team.repository.common.query.ast

Interface IString

  • All Superinterfaces:
    IFilterElement
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    IStringField, IStringInputArg, IStringLiteral, IStringScalarFunction

    public interface IString
extends IFilterElement
    Defines a common interface for all query elements that evaluate to string types. IString instances can be acquired by using IQuery.newStringArg() or by traversing through a query model to a string field.
    Since:
    0.5

    • Method Detail

      • _eq

        IPredicate _eq(IString ele)
        Returns a predicate that evaluates to true when the string value of this query element is equal to the value of the specified query element.

        NOTE: On some databases (e.g. DB2) string equality comparison behaves as if the shorter of the two strings were first padded on the right to with spaces until it is the same length as the longer string. This means, for example, that "abc" may compare equal to "abc ". If this is not acceptable then additional or different filtering may be required.

        Parameters:
        ele - the element to compare the query element to
        Returns:
        a predicate that can be used in query filters

      • _eq

        IPredicate _eq(java.lang.String value)
        Returns a predicate that evaluates to true when the string value of this query element is equal to the specified value.

        NOTE: This method should only be used if the string is known at development time. If the string is only known at runtime then input arguments are a more efficient way to construct the query.
        On some databases (e.g. DB2) string equality comparison behaves as if the shorter of the two strings were first padded on the right to with spaces until it is the same length as the longer string. This means, for example, that "abc" may compare equal to "abc ". If this is not acceptable then additional or different filtering may be required.

        IStringScalarFunction _substring(java.lang.Integer start,
                                 java.lang.Integer length)
        Returns a function that evaluates to a substring of this element's value. The substrings value starts at the start position and continues for length characters. The string indicies are 1 based.

        NOTE: This method should only be used if the values are known at development time. If the values are only known at runtime then input arguments are a more efficient way to construct the query.
